sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT trip_id) 
FROM trip_route_segments 
WHERE segment_distance > 1.60934;

external_knowledge:
- 'Trip purpose' can be locations like 'Work', 'Exercise', 'Shopping', etc.;
- 'Traffic conditions' are categorized into 'Low', 'Medium', and 'High' levels;
- The query assumes that the trip purpose can be used as a proxy for the location in the traffic conditions summary.

- "top 5 users with the highest average trip speed" refers to users who have the highest average speed across all their trips;
- "average times spent at different locations" refers to the mean time spent at four specific locations (time1, time2, time3, time4) for each trip;
- "traffic conditions" include the traffic level, date, and time of the traffic condition during the trip.

- 'Seasoned travelers' refers to users older than 25 years;
- 'Long reach' refers to an average distance traveled greater than 5 units;
- 'Spend more than 30 units of time at their destinations' means the total time spent at different locations is more than 30 units.

sql:
SELECT travel_mode
FROM travel_modes
WHERE travel_mode_id = 0;

external_knowledge:
- 'Preferred mode of transportation' refers to the mode that users have set as their preference in the system;
- 'Trips related to work, exercise, or shopping' are trips where the purpose is one of these three categories;
- 'Total distance' is the sum of distances for all trips that meet the criteria.

sql:
SELECT trip_purpose, description
FROM trip_purposes
WHERE trip_purpose_id = 1;

external_knowledge:
- "more than once" refers to users who have taken more than one trip;
- "10 units of distance" is the threshold for the total distance of a trip;
- "mode of travel" includes types like Car, Bike, Public Transportation, etc.

- 'Chosen the car as their steadfast ship' refers to users whose preferred travel mode is 'Car';
- 'Voyages' refer to trip purposes;
- 'Average distances they sail' refers to the average distance traveled for each trip purpose.

- 'Longest driving journey' refers to the trip with the maximum total trip time;
- 'Embarked on' implies the user has completed the trip;
- 'Time-consuming routes' refers to the routes with the highest summed segment times.

- 'preferred travel mode' refers to the preferred method of transportation for the user;
- 'average speed' is the mean speed calculated from all trips;
- 'average distance' is the mean distance traveled from all trips;
- 'software engineers' are users whose occupation is specifically listed as 'Software Engineer';
- 'travel pace surpasses the general flow of traffic' means the average speed of the trips is higher than the overall average speed of all trips.

- 'Public Transportation' includes modes like buses, trains, and subways;
- 'Commute' typically refers to regular travel to and from work;
- 'Low traffic conditions' imply minimal congestion and faster travel times.
